Data Cleaning¶

  • Dataset contains 7,043 rows and 21 columns
  • No missing values initially; after converting TotalCharges to numeric, 11 NA entries appeared and were removed.
  • customerID was dropped
  • Churn was encoded as Yes = 1, No = 0
  • Created telecom_cust_dummies, a one-hot–encoded version of the data (categoricals → 0/1) to use for modeling.

# Convert Churn to binary

# Create dummy variables with more control
telecom_cust_dummies = pd.get_dummies(
    df,
    columns=categorical_cols,
    prefix_sep='_',      # Explicit separator
    drop_first=False,    # Explicit about keeping all categories
    dtype='int8'         # More memory efficient than default float64
)

In [11]:
# Correlation with target (top 20 absolute) — bigger + values shown
corr_to_target = telecom_cust_dummies.corr(numeric_only=True)["Churn"].drop("Churn")
top = corr_to_target.abs().sort_values(ascending=False).head(20).index
cols = list(top) + ["Churn"]

corr = telecom_cust_dummies[cols].corr(numeric_only=True)

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 12), dpi=150)  # bigger figure
ax = sns.heatmap(
    corr,
    annot=True,           # show numbers
    fmt=".2f",            # 2 decimal places
    cmap="coolwarm",
    vmin=-1, vmax=1,      # consistent color scale
    linewidths=0.5,
    square=True,
    cbar_kws={"shrink": 0.8}
)
plt.title("Top feature correlations (with Churn)", fontsize=16, pad=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right", fontsize=9)
plt.yticks(rotation=0, fontsize=9)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • Month-to-month contract has the strongest positive link to churn (≈ +0.40): easy cancellation → higher churn.
  • No OnlineSecurity / TechSupport / OnlineBackup each ≈ +0.30–0.35: customers without these add-ons churn more (lower product “stickiness”).
  • Fiber optic internet ≈ +0.30: likely tied to higher bills/expectations.
  • Electronic check payment ≈ +0.30 and PaperlessBilling =Yes ≈ +0.19: mild positive associations with churn.
  • Higher MonthlyCharges ≈ +0.19: pricier plans churn more
  • Tenure ≈ −0.35 and Two-year contract ≈ −0.30: long relationships and long contracts reduce churn.
  • TotalCharges ≈ −0.40: customers who’ve paid more over time churn less. Note this is largely a tenure effect
  • The No internet service block (e.g., StreamingTV_No internet service, TechSupport_No internet service, etc.) are ~1.0 correlated with each other and with InternetService_NO

In [20]:
# Split the data into features and target variable
X = telecom_cust_dummies.drop(columns=['Churn'])
y = telecom_cust_dummies['Churn']

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42, stratify=y)

LOGISTIC REGRESSION¶

In [21]:
log_reg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, solver="lbfgs")
log_reg.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = log_reg.score(X_test, y_test)
print(f"Logistic Regression accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
y_pred_lr = log_reg.predict(X_test)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_lr, target_names=["No churn","Churn"]))

cm_lr = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_lr)
ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm_lr, display_labels=["No","Yes"]).plot(values_format="d")
plt.title("Logistic Regression — Confusion Matrix")
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

# Precision / Recall / F1 / Support for Random Forest

# Confusion matrix
cm_rf = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_rf)
ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm_rf, display_labels=["No", "Yes"]).plot(values_format="d")
plt.title("Random Forest — Confusion Matrix")
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

    No churn       0.83      0.91      0.87      1291
       Churn       0.66      0.49      0.56       467

    accuracy                           0.80      1758
   macro avg       0.74      0.70      0.71      1758
weighted avg       0.78      0.80      0.79      1758
  • Overall: accuracy 0.79.
  • Compared with your logistic regression (recall 0.57, F1 0.61 for churn), Random Forest is worse at catching churners though similar on accuracy.
  • The Random Forest is conservative: it rarely cries “churn” (low FP=120) but misses many actual churners. For retention, you typically want higher recall on churn, even if precision drops.

Logistic Regression VS Random Forest

  1. Error types:
    • Logistic regression (LR): TN=1147, FP=144, FN=200, TP=267
    • Random forest (RF): TN=1171, FP=120, FN=241, TP=226
    • Both models are good at identifying non-churners (high TN, specificity ≈ 0.89–0.91). The key difference is in FN (missed churners).
  2. Churn (positive class) precision vs recall:
    • LR: precision 0.65, recall 0.57, F1 0.61.
    • RF: precision 0.65, recall 0.48, F1 0.56
    • Precision is basically the same, but LR recalls ~9 percentage points more churners.In a retention setting, recall usually matters more because missed churners don’t get interventions
  3. Trade-off:
    • RF is slightly more conservative (lower FP, higher specificity) but lets more churners slip through (lower recall).
    • LR triggers a few more false alarms than RF (FP 144 vs 120) but catches more true churners, improving F1.
  4. Conclusion : confusion matrices show LR gives a better balance for churn detection: similar precision with higher recall and higher F1 on the positive class.

ENHANCED MODEL EVALUATION¶

In [26]:
def prf(y_true, y_hat):
    return (
        precision_score(y_true, y_hat, average="binary"),
        recall_score(y_true, y_hat, average="binary"),
        f1_score(y_true, y_hat, average="binary")
    )

p_lr, r_lr, f_lr = prf(y_test, y_pred_lr)
p_rf, r_rf, f_rf = prf(y_test, y_pred_rf)

print("\nPrecision/Recall/F1 (positive class = Churn=1)")
print(f"Logistic Regression →  precision={p_lr:.4f}  recall={r_lr:.4f}  f1={f_lr:.4f}")
print(f"Random Forest      →  precision={p_rf:.4f}  recall={r_rf:.4f}  f1={f_rf:.4f}")

Precision/Recall/F1 (positive class = Churn=1)
Logistic Regression →  precision=0.6504  recall=0.5696  f1=0.6073
Random Forest      →  precision=0.6552  recall=0.4882  f1=0.5595

Preferred model : Logistic regression

  • Higher recall for churn (0.572 vs 0.484) at essentially the same precision (~0.65) → more at-risk customers identified without extra noise
  • Interpretability: LR coefficients cleanly show direction/strength of drivers (e.g., month-to-month, tenure), which is valuable for business actions.
  • Comparable overall accuracy to RF (~0.80 vs ~0.79) and within typical sampling error; RF’s small accuracy gap doesn’t offset its lower churn recall.

Next Steps (either model):

  • Tune the decision threshold to target a desired recall
  • Try class_weight='balanced' to raise churn recall.
